# Final 10/10 checklist

Aqarify becomes **10/10** when all of this is true:

```txt
[ ] No critical tenant isolation bugs
[ ] No enum/API contract mismatches
[ ] No demo data in production UI
[ ] Payments are per-tenant, idempotent, and audited
[ ] Bank transfer and online payment both work
[ ] Tenant onboarding is self-serve
[ ] Tenant settings are complete
[ ] CRM/customer profile is complete
[ ] Multi-currency is complete
[ ] Regional Arabic/i18n is complete
[ ] Phone validation is country-aware
[ ] Payment gateway abstraction exists
[ ] RLS and RBAC are tested
[ ] Critical backend routes have integration tests
[ ] Critical frontend flows have E2E tests
[ ] Monitoring and alerting are live
[ ] Backups and restore are tested
[ ] Performance budget is met
[ ] UX is polished on mobile and desktop
```

## Recommended execution order

| Sprint       | Focus                                              | Expected score |
| ------------ | -------------------------------------------------- | -------------: |
| **Sprint 1** | Middleware, enums, roles, fake data removal        |     **7.2/10** |
| **Sprint 2** | Payments, webhooks, receipts, bank transfer        |       **8/10** |
| **Sprint 3** | Onboarding, tenant settings, CRM completion        |     **8.8/10** |
| **Sprint 4** | Multi-country, currency, i18n, gateway abstraction |     **9.3/10** |
| **Sprint 5** | Security, RLS, audit logs, rate limits             |     **9.7/10** |
| **Sprint 6** | Tests, CI, E2E, reliability                        |     **9.9/10** |
| **Sprint 7** | Monitoring, backups, performance, polish           |      **10/10** |

My practical recommendation: **do not chase 10/10 immediately**. First aim for **8/10**, because that is the point where Aqarify becomes commercially usable for Egypt. Then push to **9–10/10** when you want regional SaaS scale.

